div.p:
He that thus ſeriouſly conſiders what an oath is, cannot ſurely beleive that any man is above the obligation of it. So that that is an unſufferable maxime ſaid to be uſed in the Court of Rome; non eſse Regum aut Magiſtratuum, ſedmercatorum ſtare juramentis. It is not a thing confined, either to one ſort of men, or to mankind only, but reacheth even to the Angels, as we find in the Holy Scripture; 
                  Dan. 12.7. yea (with reverence be it ſpoken) God himſelf is bound by his promiſe; 
                  Rev. 10: 6. and if to any promiſe of his, an oath be ſuperadded, (which in him is an appeal to ſome one of his Attributes, but implies no execration) the Apoſtle tells us they are two immutable things. 

                  Heb. 6.18.
